{"id":"2112.09829","submitter":"Yu Sun","authors":"Adheesh Shenoy, Tianze Chen, and Yu Sun","title":"Multi-Object Grasping -- Generating Efficient Robotic Picking and\n  Transferring Policy","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.RO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Transferring multiple objects between bins is a common task for many\napplications. In robotics, a standard approach is to pick up one object and\ntransfer it at a time. However, grasping and picking up multiple objects and\ntransferring them together at once is more efficient. This paper presents a set\nof novel strategies for efficiently grasping multiple objects in a bin to\ntransfer them to another. The strategies enable a robotic hand to identify an\noptimal ready hand configuration (pre-grasp) and calculate a flexion synergy\nbased on the desired quantity of objects to be grasped. This paper also\npresents an approach that uses the Markov decision process (MDP) to model the\npick-transfer routines when the required quantity is larger than the capability\nof a single grasp. Using the MDP model, the proposed approach can generate an\noptimal pick-transfer routine that minimizes the number of transfers,\nrepresenting efficiency. The proposed approach has been evaluated in both a\nsimulation environment and on a real robotic system. The results show the\napproach reduces the number of transfers by 59% and the number of lifts by 58%\ncompared to an optimal single object pick-transfer solution.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 18 Dec 2021 03:06:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-21"}
