{"id":"2112.11919","submitter":"Sofie Cambr\\'e","authors":"Miles Martinati, Wim Wenseleers, Lei Shi, Saied Md Pratik, Philip\n  Rohringer, Weili Cui, Thomas Pichler, Veaceslav Coropceanu, Jean-Luc\n  Br\\'edas, Sofie Cambr\\'e","title":"Electronic structure of confined carbyne from joint wavelength-dependent\n  resonant Raman spectroscopy and density functional theory investigations","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.carbon.2021.12.059","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.chem-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  Carbyne, i.e. an infinitely long linear carbon chain (LCC), has been at the\nfocus of a lot of research for quite a while, yet its optical, electronic, and\nvibrational properties have only recently started to become accessible\nexperimentally thanks to its synthesis inside carbon nanotubes (CNTs). While\nthe role of the host CNT in determining the optical gap of the LCCs has been\nstudied previously, little is known about the excited states of such ultralong\nLCCs. In this work, we employ the selectivity of wavelength-dependent resonant\nRaman spectroscopy to investigate the excited states of ultralong LCCs\nencapsulated inside double-walled CNTs. In addition to the optical gap, the\nRaman resonance profile shows three additional resonances. Corroborated with\nDFT calculations on LCCs with up to 100 C-atoms, we assign these resonances to\na vibronic series of a different electronic state. Indeed, the calculations\npredict the existence of two optically allowed electronic states separated by\nan energy of 0.14-0.22 eV in the limit of an infinite chain, in agreement with\nthe experimental results. Furthermore, among these two states, the one with\nhighest energy is also characterized by the largest electron-vibration\ncouplings, which explains the corresponding vibronic series of overtones.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 18 Dec 2021 07:41:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-23"}
